What Is Machine Learning?

"Field of study that gives computers the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed." – Arthur Samuel, 1959

  • Three types:

    • Unsupervised learning.

    • Supervised learning.

    • Reinforcement learning.

Unsupervised Learning

Analogy: Give a toddler an assortment of toy cars and tell him to put the cars into groups.

  • Unlabeled data.


  • Examples include:

    • Clustering: Group types of crime in a city by medium income in that area.

    • Anomoly detection.

Supervised Learning

Analogy: Give a toddler an assortment of toys. Tell him these are cars, these are vans, and these are trucks. Then, take the toys away and present him with a new set. Tell him to identify the different types of vehicles.

  • Labeled data.


  • Examples include:

    • Using housing data for the past year, predict whether housing prices will increase or decrease next year.

    • Classify a runner's performance based on his/her gait.

    • Use image recognition with self-driving cars to tell the difference between a stop sign and a yield sign.

Reinforcement Learning

Analogy: Teach a toddler good table maners. If a toddler behaves well at dinner, reward her with a cookie. If she misbehaves, send her to her room.

  • Example:

    • A security robot at Stanford Shopping Center deciding whether to do another patrol or return to its charging station, based on its battery charge level.

Types of Machine Learning Algorithms

    • These are the labels.


  • Goal: Use machine learning to predict a wine's quality based on its chemical properties.

Outliers

  • Features with extreme values can tend to pull the model fit in the wrong direction.


  • For this demonstration, I will use a simple aproximation and define outliers as those values that are greater than five standard deviations from the mean.

    • These values will be set to the mean of that features distribution.

Removing Outliers

In [7]:
# Define function to identify outliers and set mean to feature distribution mean
def outliers(df, threshold, columns):
    for col in columns: 
        mask = df[col] > float(threshold)*df[col].std()+df[col].mean()
        df.loc[mask == True,col] = np.nan
        mean_property = df.loc[:,col].mean()
        df.loc[mask == True,col] = mean_property
    return df

# Save column names to a list
column_list = red_wine.columns.tolist()
threshold = 5

# Remove outliers for every column except the quality column
red_wine_cleaned = red_wine.copy()
red_wine_cleaned = outliers(red_wine_cleaned, threshold, column_list[0:-1])

Collinearity

  • A pair or set of features exhibiting a strong relationship with each other.


  • It poses problems for regression models.

    • Difficult to understand how each feature separately affects the response.


  • A heatmap is a useful tool to identify collinearity between features.

Heat Map

  • The Seaborn library also provides a heatmap routine.


  • It consists of a grid of plots for each feature in the data set, like the scatter plot matrix.


  • Each plot is a block of solid color showing the correlation between each feature.

    • Bluer indicates stronger negative correlation.

    • Redder indicates stronger positive correlation.

Heat Map

Removing Collinear Features

  • Perfect correlation, r = 1.0.


  • No correlation, r = 0.0.


  • Weak correlation, r < 0.5.


  • Features that show a strong correlation with another feature are:

    • fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, density, total sulfur dioxide


  • I will remove these from the feature set.

Separate Labels and Features

  • The labels are the quality values.

  • The features are everything else: fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, density, and total sulfur dioxide.

In [12]:
# Feature set
X_red_wine = red_wine_trimmed_qualities.drop('quality', axis=1)

# Labels
y_red_wine = red_wine_trimmed_qualities['quality']

# Store number of features in a variable
number_of_features = len(X_red_wine.columns)

# Store number of labels in a variable
number_of_classes = len(y_red_wine.unique())

One-hot Vectors

  • TensorFlow requires that the labels be expressed in a special way.


  • Each unique label is expressed as a vector of 0's and 1's. In our case:

    • 5 ⇒ [1, 0]

    • 7 ⇒ [0, 1]


  • These vectors are called one-hot vectors.

One-hot Vectors

In [13]:
# Reduce qualities to numbers from 0 to number of different qualities
def replace_labels(label_series):
    labels_to_replace = np.sort(label_series.unique()).tolist()
    replace_with = np.arange(len(labels_to_replace)).tolist()
    new_series = label_series.replace(to_replace=labels_to_replace, value=replace_with)
    
    return new_series

y_red_wine_list = replace_labels(y_red_wine).tolist()

# Convert labels into one-hot vectors
def dense_to_one_hot(labels_dense, num_classes=3):
    # Convert class labels from scalars to one-hot vectors
    num_labels = len(labels_dense)
    index_offset = np.arange(num_labels) * num_classes
    labels_one_hot = np.zeros((num_labels, num_classes))
    labels_one_hot.flat[index_offset + labels_dense] = 1
    return labels_one_hot

y_one_hot = dense_to_one_hot(y_red_wine_list, num_classes=number_of_classes)

Train/Test Split

  • Models in machine learning are always trained on one portion of the data set and tested on a separate set of data that the model has not seen before.


  • For this data set, I will set aside 10% of the data for testing.

In [14]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_red_wine, y_one_hot, test_size=0.1, random_state=42)

Tensor Flow

  • A machine learning library orginally developed by the Google Brain Team.

  • Graph based.
    • Nodes are operations.
    • Edges are multi-dimensional arrays called tensors.

  • All operations are done outside of Python, in a TensorFlow session.

  • Inputs are stored in a placeholder() or a Variable().
    • placeholder(): good for storing fixed input, such as the training set.
    • Variable(): good for storing variable input, such as weights and biases, which will be tuned during the modeling process.


  • These inputs are populated during the TensorFlow session.

What is a Tensor?

  • Vector: One-dimension.

  • Matrix: Two-dimensions.

  • Tensor: n-dimensions.

Image from http://noaxiom.org/tensor.

  • TensorFlow stores data in tensors.

Softmax Regression

  • For each wine, assign a probability that it is of a specific quality, in this case a 5 or a 7.


  • Softmax regression is a good method for assigning an object a probability that it is in a specific group.

Softmax Regression

  • Two steps:

    • Add up evidence that a wine is of a specific quality.

    • Convert evidence into probabilities.


  • Evidence: Weighted sum of chemical properties.

    • Negative weight: Evidence wine is not of that quality.

    • Positive weight: Evidence wine is of that quality.

Softmax Regression

  • Mathematically:

$$E_i = \sum\limits_{j}W_{i,j}x_j + b_i$$
Ei = evidence, Wi,j = weights, bi = biases, xj is the input property of the wine.


  • Convert evidence to predicted probabilites:

$$y = softmax(E)$$

Softmax Regression

  • Vector notation:

$$\begin{bmatrix}y_1 \\ y_2 \\ ... \\ y_i\end{bmatrix} = softmax\Bigg( \begin{bmatrix}W_{1,1} & W_{1,2} & ... & W_{1,j} \\ W_{2,1} & W_{2,2} & ... & W_{2,j} \\ ... & ... & ... & ... \\ W_{i,1} & W_{i,2} & ... & W_{i,j}\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ ... \\ x_i \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} b_1 \\ b_2 \\ ... \\ b_i \end{bmatrix} \Bigg)$$

  • In simpler form:

$$y = softmax(Wx + b)$$

Set Up The Model

In [15]:
# Placeholders for training features and labels
X = tf.placeholder("float", [None, number_of_features])
y = tf.placeholder("float", [None, number_of_classes])

# Variable to store weights
W = tf.Variable(tf.zeros([number_of_features, number_of_classes]), name='Weights')

# Variable to store biases
b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros([number_of_classes]), name='Biases')

Set Up The Model: TensorBoard

I will add extra code in order to prepare the visualization tool TensorBoard so we can graphically view the model.

  • I use name_scope() to organize nodes in the graph visualizer.

  • Scope is a TensorFlow library that allows the user to share variables.

In [16]:
with tf.name_scope("Wx_b") as scope:
  model = tf.nn.softmax(tf.matmul(X, W) + b)

# Define histograms for TensorBoard
w_hist = tf.histogram_summary("Weights", W)
b_hist = tf.histogram_summary("Biases", b)
y_hist = tf.histogram_summary("model", model)

Cost Function

  • A function to measure how far off the model fit is from the training data.

  • For this dataset I will use the cross-entropy function, defined as:.

$$H_{y'}(y) = -\sum\limits_{i} y'_i log(y_i) $$
y'i = training labels, yi = model

In [17]:
with tf.name_scope("cross_entropy") as scope:
  cross_entropy = tf.reduce_mean(-tf.reduce_sum(y*tf.log(model), reduction_indices=[1]))
  ce_summ = tf.scalar_summary("cross entropy", cross_entropy)

Optimization Function

  • A function to define how the cost function is minimized.


  • It uses a term called the learning rate. This says how fast the minimization should be done.

    • Too Large: Overshoot the minima.

    • Too Small: Could take forever to find the minima.


  • I will use the function gradient descent.


  • Note: There are many other types of functions that could be used.

Optimization Function

In [18]:
# Specify the learning rate
learning_rate = 0.01

# Define gradient descent function
with tf.name_scope("train") as scope:
  optimizer = tf.train.GradientDescentOptimizer(learning_rate).minimize(cross_entropy)

# Define name scope to store output accuracy of the model
with tf.name_scope("test") as scope:
  correct_prediction = tf.equal(tf.argmax(model, 1), tf.argmax(y, 1))
  accuracy = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction, "float"))
  accuracy_summary = tf.scalar_summary("accuracy", accuracy)

Batches and Epochs

During model training, it helps to gauge how the model is improving and use that to help minimize the cost. One way to do this is to divide the training data into batches.

  • Fit model to first batch.

  • Update the model.

  • Use updated model on next batch.

  • Repeat procedure to end of training data set.


This training step can be repeated many times, each time improving on the model accuracy. Each repetition is called an epoch.

Training the Model

Now it's time to train the model and output an accuracy.

In [19]:
batch_size = 120
with tf.Session() as sess:
    
    merged = tf.merge_all_summaries()
    writer = tf.train.SummaryWriter("tmp/wine_quality_logs", sess.graph)
    
    tf.initialize_all_variables().run()
    
    # Run training step 1000s times
    for i in range(1000):
        
        # Loop through training set in batches
        number_of_batches = int(len(X_train) / batch_size)
        if i % 100 == 0:
            feed = {X: X_test, y: y_test}
            result = sess.run([merged, accuracy], feed_dict=feed)
            summary_str = result[0]
            acc = result[1]
            writer.add_summary(summary_str, i)
            print("Accuracy at step %s: %s" % (i, acc))
        else:
            for start, end in zip(range(0, len(X_train), batch_size), range(batch_size, len(X_train), batch_size)):
                feed = {X: X_train[start:end], y: y_train[start:end]}
                sess.run(optimizer, feed_dict=feed)
                
    print("Final Accuracy: {0}".format(sess.run(accuracy, feed_dict={X: X_test, y: y_test})))

  • Then open TensorBoard by going to the following link: http://0.0.0.0:6006/

Why is TensorFlow better than other machine learning tools?

  • Portable to many types of hardware, from mobile devices to distributed GPUs.

  • Includes a visualization module (TensorBoard).

  • Events are logged and model training progress can be followed interactively using TensorBoard.

  • Model training is stored in checkpoints. The training can be stopped, evaluated, and then restarted at the checkpoint.

  • Open source.
